 and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":6,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":41,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes de Sanford was born in 1218, in Berkshire, England, her father, Hugh De Stanford, was 32 and her mother, Joan Noers, was 29. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Mathew Hughes. She died in 1268, in England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1218–1268":"1218–1268","1212–1242":"1212–1242","1215–1252":"1215–1252","1244–Male":"1244–Surnud","1246–1290":"1246–1290","1259–1293":"1259–1293","1187–1234":"1187–1234","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1190":"1190","1 August 1246":"1. august 1246","1187":"1187","1242":"1242","1252":"1252","14 February 1252":"14. veebruar 1252","1293":"1293","12